\section*{QMC calculations with fits}
We wish to calculate $g_\sigma\sigma$ as a function of the baryon density $\rho_B$. This can be done in the following way, consider the equation \cite{Compact}\cite{Guichon:1995ue}\cite{Bag}

\begin{figure}[t]
  \includegraphics[width=\columnwidth]{Scalar_Meson_Field}
  \caption{Mean-field values of the $\sigma$ meson for various bag radii as a function of $\rho_B$}
  \label{SMF_fit}
\end{figure}

\begin{figure}[t]
  \includegraphics[width=\columnwidth]{Effective_Mass}
  \caption{Effective mass $M_N^*$ of the nucleon as a function of the density $\rho_B$}
  \label{Meff_fit}
\end{figure}

\begin{figure}[t]
  \includegraphics[width=\columnwidth]{C_parameter}
  \caption{$C$ parameter as a function of the scalar meson $\sigma$}
  \label{C_fit}
\end{figure}
  

\begin{align}
  0 =  \sigma - \frac{g_\sigma}{m_\sigma^2}C(\sigma)\frac{2}{\pi^2}\int_0^{k_F}M_N^*(  \sigma)\frac{k^2\dd k}{\sqrt{(M_N^*(\sigma))^2+k^2}} \label{eq}
\end{align}
where
\begin{align*}
  M^*_N(\sigma) = M_N - \qty(1-\frac{a}{2}g_\sigma  \sigma)g_\sigma\sigma, \qquad C(\sigma) = 1- ag_\sigma\sigma, \qquad k_F = \qty(\frac{3\pi^2\rho_B}{2})^{1/3}
\end{align*}
where $a\approx 0.22R_B$. Note that this is for symmetric nuclear matter where $N=Z$. In non-symmetric nuclear matter we have that
\begin{align*}
  \rho_B = \rho_N + \rho_P \implies k_F^{P,N} = \qty(3\pi^2\rho_{P,N})^{1/3}
\end{align*}
and \eqref{eq} becomes\cite{RikovskaStone:2006ta}
\begin{align*}
    0 =  \sigma - \frac{g_\sigma}{m_\sigma^2}C(\sigma)\frac{1}{\pi^2}\qty(\int_0^{k_F^P}+\int_0^{k_F^N})M_N^*(  \sigma)\frac{k^2\dd k}{\sqrt{(M_N^*(\sigma))^2+k^2}} 
\end{align*}
For this report however we will only consider symmetric nuclear matter (It is understood that in the above equation, the effective nucleon mass changes for either the proton or neutron case).

So for a given density $\rho_B$, equation \eqref{eq} is entirely dependent on $\sigma$. Solving for the zeros using newtons method for the densities $0\leq \rho_B/\rho_0 \leq 2.5$ gives us the FIG. \ref{SMF_fit}. 

For completeness we may plot $M_N^*$ and $C$ as well (it should be noted that in this case we are simply plotting the fits so this is not very insightful). These are shown in FIG. \ref{Meff_fit} and FIG. \ref{C_fit}.



\section*{QMC calculations without fits}
We wish to follow the same calculations but this time without the fits. In this version we will have to solve directly for $M_N^*(\sigma)$ and $C(\sigma)$ in order to solve the integral equation (1). Consider the following:
\begin{align}
    M_N^* = \frac{3\Omega_0(\vb{R})-z_0}{R_B} +BV \label{Meff}
\end{align}
for the effective nucleon mass and the equations
\begin{align}
  C(\vb{r}) = S(\vb{r})/S(\sigma = 0), \qquad S(\vb{r}) = \frac{\Omega_0/2+m_q^*(\Omega_0-1)}{\Omega_0(\Omega_0-1)+m_q^*R_B/2} \label{C}
\end{align}
for the $C$ parameter. Partnered with
\begin{align}
  m_q^* = m_q-g_\sigma^q\sigma, \qquad g_\sigma = 3g_\sigma^qS(\sigma=0) \implies m^*_q = m_q - \frac{1}{3S(\sigma=0)}\sigma\label{mqeff}
\end{align}
\subsection*{Calculating $B$ and $z_0$}
Firstly, in order to calculate $M^*_N$ we will need to calculate the bag constant $B$ and $z_0$. This can be done via considering the free case where $\sigma = 0 \implies M^*_N = M_N = 939$ MeV for say a neutron. We will let $\Omega_0^{\text{free}}$ be the value of $\Omega_0$ that corresponds to the case where $\sigma = 0$ (It is always worth remembering that the only parameters that we fix are $R_B, m_q$ and $M_N$, everything else can be derived from these quantities).

Now the unknown variables in equation \eqref{Meff} are $\Omega_0^{\text{free}}, z_0$ and $B$. Firstly we calculate $\Omega_0^{\text{free}}$ using the following equations.
\begin{align*}
  \Omega_0^{\text{free}} = \sqrt{x^2+(m_qR_B^0)^2} ,\qquad \beta_q = \sqrt{\frac{\Omega_0^{\text{free}}-m_qR_B^0}{\Omega_0^{\text{free}}+m_qR_B^0}}
\end{align*}
where $x$ satisfies the equation. 
\begin{align*}
  j_0(x) = \beta_q j_1(x)
\end{align*}
Again we have used that for $\sigma = 0$, $m_q^* = m_q$. Written out in gory detail we have the equation
\begin{align*}
  \frac{\sin x}{x} = \qty(\frac{\sqrt{x^2+(m_qR_B^0)^2}-m_qR_B^0}{\sqrt{x^2+(m_qR_B^0)^2}+m_qR_B^0})\qty(\frac{\sin x}{x^2}-\frac{\cos x}{x})
\end{align*}
where everything is known except the variable $x$. It is worth noting down the following quantities for later as well.
\begin{align*}
  \dv{\Omega_0^{\text{free}}}{R_B} &= \qty(x^2+(m_qR_B^0)^2)^{-1/2}2\qty(m_q^2R_B+x\dv{x}{R_B}) \\
                     &= \frac{2}{\Omega_0^{\text{free}}}\qty(m_q^2R_B+x\dv{x}{R_B})
\end{align*}
where
\begin{align*}
  x = \sqrt{ \qty(\Omega_0^{\text{free}})^2-(m_qR_B)^2 }
\end{align*}
The derivative of $x$ may be calculated numerically or completely ignored as its small value doesn't contribute much to the following equations. Now Consider equation \eqref{Meff} coupled together with the equation
\begin{align}
  \dv{M_N}{R_B} = 0 \label{Meff_RB}
\end{align}
We wish to solve equations \eqref{Meff} and \eqref{Meff_RB} for the variables $z_0, B$.

Consider the following, rearranging \eqref{Meff} gives
\begin{align*}
  z_0 &= 3\Omega_0^{\text{free}}-M_NR_B+BVR_B \\
      &= 3\Omega_0^{\text{free}}-M_NR_B+B\frac{4}{3}\pi R_B^4
\end{align*}
and the differentiated equation
\begin{align*}
  \dv{M_N}{R_B} &= -\frac{1}{R_B^2}(3\Omega_0^{\text{free}}-z_0)+\frac{1}{R_B}3\dv{\Omega_0^{\text{free}}}{R_B}+B4\pi R_B^2 \\
  0 &= -\frac{1}{R_B^2}\qty(M_NR_B-B\frac{4}{3}\pi R_B^4)+\frac{1}{R_B}3\dv{\Omega_0^{\text{free}}}{R_B}+B4\pi R_B^2  \\
  0 &= -M_NR_B + B\frac{4}{3}\pi R_B^4 + 3R_B\dv{\Omega_0^{\text{free}}}{R_B} + B4\pi R_B^4 \\
  M_N - 3\dv{\Omega_0^{\text{free}}}{R_B} &= B\qty( \frac{4}{3}\pi R_B^3 + 4\pi R_B^3 ) \\
  B &= \frac{3}{R_B^3}\frac{ M_N -3\dd \Omega_0^{\text{free}}/\dd R_B }{4\pi+12\pi} \\
  &= \frac{3}{16\pi R_B^3}\qty(M_N - 3\dv{\Omega_0^{\text{free}}}{R_B} )
\end{align*}
So the Bag constant $B$ and $z_0$ may be calculated via the simple formula (after solving for $\Omega_0^{\text{free}}$ via the boundary problem)
\begin{align*}
  B &= \frac{3}{16\pi R_B^3}\qty(M_N - 3\dv{\Omega_0^{\text{free}}}{R_B} ) \\
  z_0 &= 3\Omega_0^{\text{free}}-M_NR_B+B\frac{4}{3}\pi R_B^4
\end{align*}
\subsection*{Calculating $C$}
\begin{align*}
  C(\vb{r}) = S(\vb{r})/S(\sigma = 0)
\end{align*}
We need to use \eqref{C} and \eqref{mqeff} to solve for $C$. Firstly we may calculate $S(\sigma=0)$ simply using our value for $\Omega_0^{\text{free}}$
\begin{align*}
S(\sigma=0) = \frac{\Omega_0^{\text{free}}/2+m_q\qty(\Omega_0^{\text{free}}-1)}{\Omega_0^{\text{free}}\qty(\Omega_0^{\text{free}}-1)+m_qR_B/2}   
\end{align*}
where $\Omega_0^{\text{free}}$ is the $\Omega_0$ calculated in the previous part. Equation \eqref{mqeff} can also be written as
\begin{align}
  m^*_q = m_q - \frac{1}{3S(\sigma=0)}g_\sigma\sigma \label{mqef}
\end{align}
Now $C\equiv C(\sigma)$ i.e. it is a function of $\sigma$ (We assume that $g_\sigma$ is known). Suppose that we where given a value for $\sigma$. We could then solve the boundary problem
\begin{align*}
    j_0(x) = \beta_q j_1(x)
\end{align*}
where now $m_q \to m_q^*$ which may be calculated from \eqref{mqef} to find our new $\Omega_0$. This $\Omega_0$ is then used with $m_q^*$ to calculate $S(\vb{r})$. We can then use \eqref{C} to calculate $C$.
\subsection*{Calculating $M_N^*$}
\begin{align*}
      M_N^* = \frac{3\Omega_0(\vb{R})-z_0}{R_B} +BV 
\end{align*}
Now given a value of $\sigma$, we calculate $\Omega_0$ using the same procedure we used for calculating $C$. We then make use of the values for $B$ and $z_0$ from the free case and can hence calculate $M^*_N$ for this value of $\sigma$.

\subsection*{Calculating the spin orbit correction}
Similarly as above we just apply the following formulas to calculate $I(\vb{R})$ and $I_0$
\begin{align*}
  I(\vb{R}) = \frac{R_B}{3}\qty(\frac{4\Omega_0+2m_q^*R_B-3}{2\Omega_0(\Omega_0-1)+m^*_qR_B}), \qquad I_0 = \frac{R_B}{3}\qty(\frac{4\Omega_0^{\text{free}}+2m_q^*R_B-3}{2\Omega_0^{\text{free}}(\Omega_0^{\text{free}}-1)+m^*_qR_B})
\end{align*}

\subsection*{\underline{Important Note}}
When doing these calculations it is VITAL to convert all units to powers of MeV. All the quantities in these calculations should be in either powers of MeV or fm. One may simply make use of the conversion factor
\begin{align*}
  \text{fm} = \frac{1}{197.33}\text{MeV}^{-1}
\end{align*}
\subsection*{Calculating the Scalar Meson Field}
Using these methods we then have that our equation \eqref{eq} only depends on the parameter $\sigma$ (i.e. given a value for $\sigma$ we can calculate all these parameters provided we have set $M_N$, $R_B$ and $m_q$).

So for a given density $\rho_B$, we find the value of $\sigma$ that solves the equation \eqref{eq} (via Newton's method or some other similar method). It is important to note that in this method, every time we choose a new value of sigma to try and solve equation \eqref{eq} we have to solve the bag equations for $M^*_N$ and $C$.

To make matters quicker we may solve for a linear and quadratic for $M^*_N$ and $C$ (This is where the fits from the first part come from). If one plots the values for $C$ vs $g_\sigma\sigma$ one finds that the function is linear hence
\begin{align*}
  C(g_\sigma\sigma) = b-ag_\sigma\sigma, \qquad a,b\inR
\end{align*}
where $a>0$ (This is known from plotting the values of $C$ directly from solving the Bag equations and seeing that it has negative slope). However we note that
\begin{align*}
  C(\sigma = 0) = \frac{S(\sigma = 0)}{S(\sigma = 0)} = 1 \implies b = 1
\end{align*}
so the coefficient $a$ may be simply calculated via
\begin{align*}
  a = \frac{1-C(g_\sigma\sigma)}{g_\sigma\sigma}
\end{align*}
where we only need to solve the bag equations at one $\sigma$ value to obtain the value $C(g_\sigma\sigma)$ hence allowing us to calculate the coefficient $a$.

To calculate the fit to $M_N^*$, we note that
\begin{align*}
  C(g_\sigma\sigma)g_\sigma(\sigma=0) = -\pdv{\sigma}\qty(M^*_N)
\end{align*}
where $g_\sigma(\sigma=0) = g_\sigma$. Hence integrating our fit gives us that
\begin{align*}
  -M^*_N &= -c+\qty(\sigma-\frac{a}{2}g_\sigma\sigma^2)g_\sigma \\
           M^*_N &= c-\qty(1-\frac{a}{2}g_\sigma\sigma)g_\sigma\sigma
\end{align*}
We also know that $M^*_N(\sigma=0) = M_N$ hence
\begin{align*}
             M^*_N &= M_N-\qty(1-\frac{a}{2}g_\sigma\sigma)g_\sigma\sigma
\end{align*}
This gives us our fits.

So in order to calculate the scalar meson field values, we can either solve \eqref{eq} by solving the bag equations every time we choose a new value of $\sigma$ or instead solving the bag equations a certain number of times and calculating the value of the parameter $a$ using the above formula (using a few values for $\sigma$ and averaging gives a more precise value for $a$).

We would then proceed as we did in the first part to calculate the scalar meson field values.

\subsection*{Results}
Following the above procedures but choosing to do it the hard way by calculating the bag equations at every step gives the following results

\begin{table}
  \begin{center}
    \begin{tabular}{|| c c c c ||}
      \hline
      $R_B^0$(fm) & 0.6 & 0.8 & 1.0 \\
      \hline \hline
      $B^{1/4}$ & 211.335 & 170.321 & 144.074 \\
      $z_0$ & 4.008 & 3.301 & 2.594 \\
      $a$ (MeV$^{-1}$) & 0.69E-03 & 0.92E-03 & 0.11E-02 \\
      \hline
    \end{tabular}
    \caption{Values for relevant constants calculated for various bag radii}
  \end{center}
\end{table}

